SIMPLE: overreach
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Overreach
<hw>O`ver*reach"</hw> <pr>(⟦omac⟧`v⟦etil⟧r*r⟦emac⟧ch")</pr>, <pos>v.
t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Overreached</conjf>
<pr>(?)</pr>, (<conjf>Overraught</conjf> <pr>(<?/)</pr>,
<mark>obs.</mark>); <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Overreaching</conjf>.]</vmorph>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To reach above or beyond in any direction.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To deceive, or get the better of, by artifice or
cunning; to outwit; to cheat.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To defeat one's own purpose by trying to do too much
or by trying too hard or with excessive eagerness; -- used reflexively;
<as>as, the candidate <ex>overreached</ex> himself by trying to plant
false rumors, which backfired</as>/</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Overreach</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Overreach
<hw>O`ver*reach"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To reach too
far</def>; as: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>To strike the toe of the hind foot
against the heel or shoe of the forefoot; -- said of horses.</def>
<sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To sail on one tack farther than is
necessary.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cheat by cunning or deception.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1024 --></p>

<p><ent>Overreach</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Overreach
<hw>O"ver*reach`</hw> <pr>(⟦omac⟧"v⟦etil⟧r*r⟦emac⟧ch`)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <def>The act of striking the heel of the fore foot with
the toe of the hind foot; -- said of horses.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Overreacher</ent>⟦br⟧
